sv:property.sv:value: All authoring tasks such as managing the site hierarchy and inline editing are carried out in a browser. No more client installations, no platform dependencies.
Move or copy entire site-structures with ease. Reorder pages and page-content via drag and drop – directly in the browser.
Magnolia’s web addresses are indistinguishable from static URLs. This makes them easy to read, easy to communicate, easy to bookmark and easy to spider by search engines.

Define roles for document access and assign them to your users to make sure each user has only the rights that he or she should have. Documents can only be seen, read and changed by those who are allowed to do so.
Magnolia automatically saves meta-data such as the name of an author and the last authoring date.
Each Magnolia user can choose to work with Magnolia in in of currently 15 languages. Additionally, it is straightforward to serve content in several languages by creating one site tree per language.
Multilanguage - admin in 15 languages; content in any language

A centrally managed file library allows you to reference reference files from your content pages and thus allows the reuse of digital assets through out your site. A powerfull meta-data driven search interface makes finding these assets easy.
Magnolia can be set up in such a way that workgroups have shared access to resources, e.g. a folder in the document management system.
(*) denotes features of the Enterprise Edition

Magnolia has integrated a leading cross-platform workflow engine, which allows for extensive customization of workflows and the integration of Magnolia as part of a business process managed architecture.
Magnolia's integrated full-text search easily lets you find what you are looking for.
Freely customizable meta data fields allows you to categorize and retrieve content based not on the content itself, but on information about the content.

The combination of meta data information and a powerful workflow engine allows you to activate (publish) content based on anything - for example, content can be published (or unpublished) based on date and time.

Magnolia comnes with a powerful set of templates that let you create a large set of different designs without programming. Additionally, you can create custom templates for limitless integration and customization options.
Design your site inside the browser (*)
(*) denotes features of the Enterprise Edition
Magnolia content can be displayed in a portlet. It allows customization and personalization. Magnolia itself is able to run inside a JSR-168 portal.
RSS feeds of Magnolia pages are available through the standard templates.

Magnolia is using JAAS for authentication and authorization. This standard allows to use various systems to authenticate and authorize access to Magnolia, and provides options for single-sign-on. A JCRLoginModule as well as a standard LDAP/ADS login module are provided so that users can be managed externally.
Authentication, Single Sign On, JAAS and directory support (*)
(*) denotes features of the Enterprise Edition

The deployment module lets you create packages from Magnolia resources - static resources, configuration data, templates and java classes. It allows you to exchange templates and paragraphs between people or installations in a standard format and provides provides install / uninstall functionality, deployment mechanisms (activate your changes). In addition it can be used to provide backup functionality of complete site designs or groups of functionality (not only content).

Backup is possible through various means - either provided through the repository itself (CRX allows hot backup), or through the import/export mechanism, which can be scheduled through an external scheduler. In addition, the new deployment module (*) allows to backup content, java classes, templates and static resources as a single package.

Magnolia uses the JSR-170 standard API to access its content. This makes content storage independent of the CMS and allows the usage of various implementations. Magnolia is delivered with an open source repository. For high end requirements, CRX - the leading commercial repository - is available as an option.
The integrated publish & subscribe mechanism allows you to mirror your website to as many physically distributed servers as you want.

Magnolia has its own caching mechanism to increase speed and minimize CPU load. The cache is written on the file system and is automatically updated whenever needed. It is configurable by tree or by page.
The built-in publish & subscribe mechanism allows you to syndicate content easily to any other application which understands HTTP.
Magnolia uses standard Log4j logging. Its extensive customization options allow you to focus logs on your particular needs.
(*) denotes features of the Enterprise Edition
Form dialogs for data entry are generated automatically. You concentrate on the “what” – Magnolia provides the “how”.
Utilize your existing Java knowledge – no need to learn proprietary script languages any more.
Standards-based templating in JSP and Servlets

The Magnolia tag libraries allow you to customize the authoring environment and create templates in a fast, efficient and re-usable way. Magnolia additionally supports third-party tag libraries such as JSTL to minimize the amount of code you have to write.

Site templating by default is done in JSP and allows unlimited page and paragraph designs. The templating engine is pluggable and can be replaced by other implementations - for instance FreeMarker or Velocity. Magnolia gives you the flexibility you want while preserving corporate design guidelines.

Magnolia 3.5 will use Spring for even easier customization and integration. Magnolia 3.0 is already prepared for that step and many functionalities are pluggable, i.e. can be replaced by your own custom implementation without recompiling Magnolia itself.
(*) denotes features of the Enterprise Edition

Magnolia is the name of a content management software that has originally been developed by obinary Ltd., a privatly held Swiss software company. Obinary first released its open-source "Magnolia Content Management" on November 15th, 2003.

Magnolia quickly became the CMS of choice around the world for new content management installations based on JSR-170 and Java due to its enterprise architecture, its use of standards (like JSR-170) and its easy-to-use web-interface. It is used around the world in several thousand installations.

Subsequently, Magnolia Organization, a 100% daughter of obinary, was handling legal aspects of the source code, as well as partnerships, certifications etc. while obinary was selling services around Magnolia.

Obinary then started to create commercial products, now available as "Magnolia Enterprise Edition" and "Magnolia Business Process Edition".

Since Obinary's business is now solely based on services and license sales of Magnolia products, it is in the process of changing its company name to "Magnolia International Ltd.".
A very brief history of Magnolia

Magnolia 3.0 is the first commercial open-source Enterprise Content Management System that seamlessly integrates web content management and document management through one intuitive, web-based, AJAX-powered user interface.

Magnolia uses the standard API for java content repositories (JCR) (JSR-170) to access its content.
